<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06022099 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06022099 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MIDEAST; WAR; QA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  These are questions Mercury News readers have frequently asked about thePersian Gulf war. If you have a question, we'll try to answer it. Call ourspecial reader question line at (408) 920-5958 and leave your question on therecording. If the recording cannot accept any more calls, please try againlater. We'll answer as many questions as possible in future editions.;    QIraq has fired nearly two dozen Scud missiles at Israel and Saudi Arabia, yetthere has been little damage and few casualties. Why do people fear thesemissiles?  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SHRIEK OF SCUD MISSILES TERRORIZES  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  War in the GulfSee also related article on page 1A and 8A-12A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     A The missiles, which can be wildly inaccurate, make a shrieking sound asthey descend and that noise often terrorizes those under attack. They alsohave great potential to cause death and limited destruction upon impact. Thepossibility that these missiles may contain chemical warheads adds to thefear. Iranian officials said during the final years of the Iran-Iraq war thatthey had a tremendous psychological effect on Iran's population.;    Q Whatdoes Scud stand for?;    A It's a code name given the Soviet-designed SS-1missile by NATO forces.;    Q Who makes the Patriot missile?;    A ThePatriot, used to shoot down incoming missiles like the Scud, is designed bythe Raytheon Co. of Lexington, Mass. The Picatinny Arsenal in New Jerseydeveloped the warhead and arming device; Morton Thiokol Inc. in Huntsville,Ala., makes the solid fuel motors; Raytheon's Andover, Mass., plantmanufactures the radar guidance system; and Texas Instruments in Dallas makesa computer component that is put into the tail of the missile. The missilescost about $500,000 each.;    Q If Jordan is trying to stay neutral, why is itpermitting Iraqi missiles to fly over it and hit Israel?;    A Jordan has saidit will not permit a country to violate its airspace, but enforcing that standis a different matter. For example, Jordan lacks the anti-missile system thatwould be needed to shoot down Iraqi Scud missiles aimed at Israel. But Jordanhas weapons that can bring down planes that might be used by Israel toretaliate against Iraq.;    Q When did Saddam use chemical weapons against hisown people?;    A In 1988, Iraqi planes allegedly dropped chemicals on thenorthern towns of Kurdistan and Halabja to put down a rebellion. However,analysts at the U.S. Army War College last summer questioned those reports,suggesting that the Kurds might have been injured by fuel-air explosivesinstead of chemical weapons.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Compiled by Mercury News Staff Writer Gary Richards through Mercury News wirereports, the Pentagon, Middle East experts at the Hoover Institution and theRand Corp.  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910122  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  427  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday January 22, 199100022099,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>